Isolation of cardiomyocytes undergoing mitosis with complete cytokinesis.

This document documents how the gene expression data was analyzed and the figures produced or supporting data files are available from the project github repository. Compiling (kniting) the source document in RStudio (or from the command line) will regenerate key panes off figures 5 and 6 from the source data as they appear in the manuscript. Note that due to the large data files, cloning the repository requires that you have large file support for git installed. Otherwise, you will only receive the soft links to the data files, not the data files themselves.

This repository provides processed data necessary to perform the analysis and generate figures. Raw data (both fastqs and 10X genomics mtx files) have been submitted to GEO and are available under accession GSE138270.

0.3 Background

Pharmacologic and interventional advances over the past two decades have produced a substantial reduction in mortality related to coronary artery disease (CAD). However, while mortality is on the decline, prevalance of the sequelae of CADmost notably dilated cardiomyopathy and heart failureare on the rise. Restoration of function among patient experiencing ischemia or infarct related to CAD requires replenishment of cardiomyocytes within the failing myocardium. Our past work has demonstrated that the heart has only limited regenerative capacity in this regard. Therefore, it is of utmost importance to be able to identify those cardiomyocytes with proflierative potential, either for the purposes of local delivery of these cells or to identify new pharmacologic strategies for stimulating cardiomyocyte profiferation.

Conventional markers of cell cycle progression based on DNA content are not useful for identifying proliferating cardiomoycytes. This is due to the fact that while cardiomyocytes rarely complete cell division, they commonly enter the cell cycle but arrest prior to cytokinesis.

Here we combine molecular beacon technology with single cell RNASeq profiling to identify and chracterize a population of cardimoyocytes enriched for cells with proliferative potential.

# For post-hoc analysis, we can do this in the conventional t-test way

compare_slopes <- function(dat, var1, var2) {
  fit1 <- lm(value ~ Time, data=subset(dat, variable==var1))
  fit2 <- lm(value ~ Time, data=subset(dat, variable==var2))
  cf1 <- summary(fit1)$coef
  df <- summary(fit1)$df[2] # already penalized by 2
  
  cf2 <- summary(fit2)$coef
  df <- df + summary(fit2)$df[2] # already penalized by 2 more
  
  ts <- abs(cf2[2,1] - cf1[2,1]) / sqrt(cf2[2,2]**2 + cf1[2,2]**2)
  2 * dt(ts, df)
}

0.5 Differential gene expression analysis

Here we use the pagoda2 package to normalize the gene counts and then identify genes that are (1) differentially expressed between each group of cells vs.the other groups and (2) also on average more highly expressed in each group vs.both the other groups. We will restrict our analysis to cells that are TMEM88 or TNNT2 positive (cardiomyocytes and/or cardiomyocyte progenitors).

The code below shows how the raw counts were extracted from the 10X Chromium run and how they were filtered. The raw output from the 10X Chromium pipeline is not provided here due to file size (but is available from GEO), but this repository contains the filtered raw counts for use in both the pagoda and AUCell analyses below.

root <- "./final_data/outs/"

countMatrix <- read.10x.matrices(
  paste0(root, "filtered_gene_bc_matrices_mex/GRCh38/")
)
cd <- clean.counts(as.matrix(countMatrix), 
                   min.lib.size=1000, 
                   min.reads = 1, 
                   min.detected = 1)
cd <- apply(cd, 2, function(x) { storage.mode(x) <- 'integer'; x})
colnames(cd) <- gsub("^.*_", "", colnames(cd))

# restrict to cardiomyocytes or cardiomyocyte precursors
ix <-  which(rownames(cd) == "TMEM88")[1]
ix2 <-  which(rownames(cd) == "TNNT2")[1]
cd <- cd[, which(cd[ix,] > 0 | cd[ix2,] > 0)]

# these raw counts are used later by AUCell
saveRDS(cd, "final_data/filtered_count_matrix.rds")

#normalize and filter using pagoda defaults
counts <- gene.vs.molecule.cell.filter(cd)
#counts <- counts[ rowSums(as.matrix(counts)) >= 10,]
rownames(counts) <- make.unique(rownames(counts))
saveRDS(counts, file="final_data/counts.rds")
pag <- Pagoda2$new(counts, log.scale = TRUE, n.cores = 8)
pag$adjustVariance(plot = FALSE, gam.k = 10)
pag <- saveRDS(pag, file="final_data/pagoda_object.rds")

0.6 Functional Analysis

0.6.1 Cell cycle gene enrichment

We can examine the functional the differentially expressed genes identified above by calculating enrichment in GO terms via the hypergeometric test. The most enriched terms are shown in the figure 5b & c, generated below.

# note that using SYMBOLS causes enrichGO to fail (as it tries to convert 
# the SYMBOLS to SYMBOLS which results in fewer columns of gene ids than 
# the function expects).  So we convert to entrez gene id.

symToEg <- function(x) {
  ix <- which(x %in% ls(org.Hs.egSYMBOL2EG))
  eg <- unlist(mget(x[ix], org.Hs.egSYMBOL2EG))
  return(unique(eg))
}

We can further analyze the functional difference in these cells by performing gene set enrichment analysis (via the AUCell algorithm) using established cell cycle signature. To begin, we define a plotting function for AUC scores to color by cell group and facet by signature, while simultaneously reporting results of analysis for equivalence of central tendency between groups using permutation based methods and reporting adjusted pair-wise post-hoc comparisons (again using permutation based methods due to non-equivalence of variances and non-normality of some data strata).

library(ggplot2)
library(ggpubr)
## Loading required package: magrittr
## 
## Attaching package: 'ggpubr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:plyr':
## 
##     mutate
# set dryrun = TRUE to test the plotting without permutation based sig tests (much 
# faster for optimizing plot labels, etc.). The test parameter should be one of 
# 't', 'perm', or 'auto' (in which case the permutation based test is used only if 
# abs(skewness(data$value)) > 0.5)
plot_auc <- function(data, title = " ", 
                     comparisons, 
                     adjust=TRUE, 
                     test="auto",
                     dryrun = FALSE, 
                     scales = "fixed") {
  # normality and variance diagnostics
  print(ggqqplot(data, x = "value", facet.by = c("class", "variable")))

  skewed <- abs(skewness(data$value)) > 0.5
  print(paste0("SKEWNESS ", skewness(data$value)))
  
  ttest <- function(a,b) {
    p <- t.test(a, b, var.equal=FALSE)$p.value
    if(adjust) {
      p <- p * (length(comparisons) * length(levels(data$variable)))
    }
    p <- ifelse(p < 0.0001, "<0.0001", round(p,4))
    p <- ifelse(p > 0.05, "ns", p)
    return(list(p.value = p))
  }  
  
  permtest <- function(a, b) {
    if(dryrun) return(list(p.value="dryrun"))
    d <- c(a,b)
    grp <- c(rep('a', length(a)),
             rep('b', length(b)))
    dat <- data.frame(value=d, group=grp)
    set.seed(1000)
    p <- GFD::GFD(value ~ grp, data=dat, nperm = 100000)$WTS["p-value WTPS"]
    if(adjust) {
      p <- p * (length(comparisons) * length(levels(data$variable)))
    }
    p <- ifelse(p < 0.0001, "<0.0001", round(p,4))
    p <- ifelse(p > 0.05, "ns", p)
    list(p.value=p)
  }
  
  # diagnostics
  if(test == "perm" || (test == "auto" && skewed)) {
    if(length(levels(data$variable)) > 1 && !dryrun) {
      print("Permuted Wald Type Test (GFD package):")
      tr.gfd <- GFD::GFD(value ~ class + variable, data = data)
      print(tr.gfd)
    } else if (!dryrun) {
      print("Permuted Wald Type Test (GFD package):")
      tr.gfd <- GFD::GFD(value ~ class, data = data)
      print(tr.gfd)
    }
  } else {
     if(!dryrun) {
        print("### ONE WAY ANOVA")
        print(summary(aov(value ~ class, data=data)))
     }
     if(length(levels(data$variable)) > 1 && !dryrun) {
      print("TWO WAY ANOVA:")
      rv <- data$value
      print(summary(aov(rv ~ class + variable, data=data)))
     }
  }
  
  if(test == "perm" || (test == "auto" && skewed)) {
    print(" ##### USING PERMUTATION BASED SIGNIFICANCE TESTING ####")
    sigtest <- permtest
  } else {
    print(" ##### USING PARAMETRIC SIGNIFICANCE TESTING ####")
    sigtest <- ttest
  }

  p <- ggplot(data, aes(class, value)) +
    geom_jitter(aes(color = class), 
                height = 0.01, 
                width = 0.1, 
                alpha = 0.5, 
                shape = 20, size = 1) +
    geom_violin(alpha = 0.3) +
    ggsignif::geom_signif(comparisons = comparisons, family = font_family,
                          textsize = 3,
                          vjust = -.2,
                          step_increase = .18,
                          test=sigtest) +
    theme_bw() + 
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0.2, 0)) +
    ggtitle(title) +
    theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
      axis.text.x=element_blank(),
      axis.ticks.x=element_blank()) +
    ylab("AUC Enrichment Score") +
    facet_wrap(~variable, 
               ncol = 3, 
               scales = scales)
  p
}

We then load the cell cycle signatures defined by McCarroll et al.and Glotzer et al, calculate enrichment scores for each signature and each cell and plot results.

tab2sig <- function(file) {
  data <- read.delim(file, as.is=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, header=TRUE)
  res <- apply(data, 2, function (x) {
    x <- gsub(" ", "", x)
    x <- x[which(x != "")]
  })
  res
}

auc_mccaroll <- function(dryrun = FALSE) {
  sigs <- tab2sig("final_data/signatures/cell_cycle_mccarroll.txt")
  set.seed(1000)
  cells_rankings <- AUCell_buildRankings(cd, nCores=12, plotStats=FALSE)
  cells_AUC <- AUCell_calcAUC(sigs, cells_rankings)
  dat <- as.data.frame(t(getAUC(cells_AUC)))
  dat$class <- sg
  dat <- melt(dat, id.vars = c("class"))
  dat$class <- factor(dat$class, labels = c("G1-CDC20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20+"))
  comparisons <- list( c("G2/M-CDC20+", "G2/M-CDC20-"),  
                   c("G1-CDC20-", "G2/M-CDC20-"), 
                   c("G1-CDC20-", "G2/M-CDC20+"))


  plot_auc(dat, test="auto", comparisons = comparisons, dryrun = dryrun) +
    scale_color_discrete(labels=c(expression(paste("G1-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^high)))) +
    theme(legend.text.align = 0) +
    labs(color="")
}

      guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 4)))

auc_glotzer <- function(dryrun = FALSE) {
  sigs <- tab2sig("final_data/signatures/CYTOKINESES_GLOTZER.txt")
  sigs <- as.data.frame(sigs)
  set.seed(1000)
  cells_rankings <- AUCell_buildRankings(cd, nCores=4, plotStats=FALSE)
  cells_AUC <- AUCell_calcAUC(sigs, cells_rankings)
  dat <- as.data.frame(t(getAUC(cells_AUC)))
  dat$class <- sg
  dat <- melt(dat, id.vars = c("class"))
  dat$class <- factor(dat$class, labels = c("G1-CDC20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20+"))
  comparisons <- list( c("G2/M-CDC20+", "G2/M-CDC20-"),  
                   c("G1-CDC20-", "G2/M-CDC20-"), 
                   c("G1-CDC20-", "G2/M-CDC20+"))
  plot_auc(dat, title=" ", comparisons = comparisons, dryrun = dryrun) + 
    scale_color_discrete(labels=c(expression(paste("G1-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^high)))) +
    theme(legend.text.align = 0)
}

auc_mccaroll_spg <- function(dryrun = FALSE) {
  sigs <- tab2sig("final_data/signatures/cell_cycle_mccarroll.txt")
  set.seed(1000)
  cells_rankings <- AUCell_buildRankings(cd, nCores=12, plotStats=FALSE)
  cells_AUC <- AUCell_calcAUC(sigs, cells_rankings)
  dat <- as.data.frame(t(getAUC(cells_AUC)))
  dat$class <- sg
  dat <- melt(dat, id.vars = c("class"))
  dat$class <- factor(dat$class, labels = c("G1-CDC20-SPG20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20-SPG20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20+SPG20-",

  comparisons <- list( c("G2/M-CDC20+SPG20-", "G2/M-CDC20+SPG20+"))

    theme(legend.text.align = 0) +
    labs(color="")
}

auc_glotzer_spg <- function(dryrun = FALSE) {
  sigs <- tab2sig("final_data/signatures/CYTOKINESES_GLOTZER.txt")
  sigs <- as.data.frame(sigs)
  set.seed(1000)
  cells_rankings <- AUCell_buildRankings(cd, nCores=4, plotStats=FALSE)
  cells_AUC <- AUCell_calcAUC(sigs, cells_rankings)
  dat <- as.data.frame(t(getAUC(cells_AUC)))
  dat$class <- sg
  dat <- melt(dat, id.vars = c("class"))
  dat$class <- factor(dat$class, labels = c("G1-CDC20-SPG20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20-SPG20-", 
                                        "G2/M-CDC20+SPG20-",
                                        "G2/M-CDC20+SPG20+"))
  comparisons <- list( c("G2/M-CDC20+SPG20-", "G2/M-CDC20+SPG20+")) 
  plot_auc(dat, comparisons = comparisons, dryrun = dryrun) +
    scale_color_discrete(labels=c(expression(paste("G1-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low, italic("SPG20"), ""^low,)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^low, italic("SPG20"), ""^low,)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^high, italic("SPG20"), ""^low,)),
                                  expression(paste("G2/M-", italic("CDC20"), ""^high, italic("SPG20"), ""^high,)))) +
    theme(legend.text.align = 0)
}

p <- auc_glotzer_spg() +
    labs(color="") + 
    guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 4)))
